1901: EC8A         ;---------------------- Set File Attributes - 1E (30) ----------------------;
1902: EC8A         ;  This function sets the bits that describe attributes of a file in the    ;
1903: EC8A         ; relevant directory entries for the specified file. Each file can be       ;
1904: EC8A         ; assigned up to 11 file attributes. Of these 11, two have predefined       ;
1905: EC8A         ; meanings, four others are available for you to use, and the remaining     ;
1906: EC8A         ; five are reserved for future use by CP/M.                                 ;
1907: EC8A         ;  Each attribute consists of a single bit. The most significant bit of     ;
1908: EC8A         ; each byte of the file name and type is used to store the attributes.      ;
1909: EC8A         ; The file attributes are known by a code consisting of the letter "f"      ;
1910: EC8A         ; (for file name) or "t" (for file type), followed by the number of the     ;
1911: EC8A         ; character position and a single quotation mark. For example, the Read-Only;
1912: EC8A         ; attribute is tl'.                                                         ;
1913: EC8A         ;	The significance of the attributes is as follows:                       ;
1914: EC8A         ;			fl' to f4' Available for you to use                             ;
1915: EC8A         ;			f5' to fS' Reserved for future CP/M use                         ;
1916: EC8A         ;			tl' Read-Only File attribute                                    ;
1917: EC8A         ;			t2' System File attribute                                       ;
1918: EC8A         ;			t3' Reserved for future CP/M use                                ;
1919: EC8A         ;			                                                                ;
1920: EC8A         ;  Attributes are set by presenting this function with an FCB in which the  ;
1921: EC8A         ; unambiguous file name has been preset with the most significant bits      ;
1922: EC8A         ; set appropriately. This function then searches the directory for a match  ;
1923: EC8A         ; and changes the matched entries to contain the attributes which have been ;
1924: EC8A         ; set in the FCB.                                                           ;
1925: EC8A         ;  The BDOS will intercept any attempt to write on a file that has the      ;
1926: EC8A         ; Read-Only attribute set. The DIR command in the CCP does not display any  ;
1927: EC8A         ; file with System status.                                                  ;
1928: EC8A         ;                                                                           ;
1929: EC8A         ;  You can use the four attributes available to you to set up a file        ;
1930: EC8A         ; security system, or perhaps to flag certain files that must be backed up  ;
