1972: ECAB         ;------------------------- Read Random - 21 (33) ---------------------------;
1973: ECAB         ; This function reads a specific CP/M record (128 bytes) from a random file ;
1974: ECAB         ; that is, a file in which records can be accessed directly. It assumes that;
1975: ECAB         ; you have already opened the file, set the DMA address using the BDOS      ;
1976: ECAB         ; Set DMA function, and set the specific record to be read into the random  ;
1977: ECAB         ; record number in the FCB. This function computes the extent of the        ;
1978: ECAB         ; specified record number and attempts to open it and read the correct CP/M ;
1979: ECAB         ; record into the DMA address.                                              ;
1980: ECAB         ;  The random record number in the FCB is three bytes long (at relative     ;
1981: ECAB         ; bytes 33, 34, and 35). Byte 33 is the least significant byte, 34 is the   ;
1982: ECAB         ; middle byte, and 35 the most significant. CP/M uses only the most         ;
1983: ECAB         ; significant byte (35) for computing the overall file size (function 35).  ;
1984: ECAB         ; You must set this byte to 0 when setting up the FCB. Bytes 33 and 34      ;
1985: ECAB         ; are used together for the Read Random, so you can access from record      ;
1986: ECAB         ; 0 to 65535 (a maximum file size of 8,388,480 bytes).                      ;
1987: ECAB         ;  This function returns with A set to 0 to indicate that the operation has ;
1988: ECAB         ; been completed successfully, or A set to a nonzero value if an error has  ;
1989: ECAB         ; occurred. The error codes are as follows:                                 ;
1990: ECAB         ;		A = 01 (attempt to read unwritten record)                           ;
1991: ECAB         ;		A = 03 (CP/M could not close current extent)                        ;
1992: ECAB         ;		A = 04 (attempt to read unwritten extent)                           ;
1993: ECAB         ;		A = 06 (attempt to read beyond end of disk)                         ;
1994: ECAB         ;		                                                                    ;
1995: ECAB         ;  Unlike the Read Sequential BOOS function (code 20, l4H), which updates   ;
1996: ECAB         ; the current (sequential) record number in the FCB, the Read Random        ;
1997: ECAB         ; function leaves the record number unchanged, so that a subsequent Write   ;
1998: ECAB         ; Random will replace the record just read.                                 ;
1999: ECAB         ;  You can follow a Read Random with a Write Sequential (code 21, l5H).     ;
2000: ECAB         ; This will rewrite the record just read, but will then update the          ;
2001: ECAB         ; sequential record number. Or you may choose to use a Read Sequential after;
2002: ECAB         ; the Read Random. In this case, the same record will be reread and the     ;
2003: ECAB         ; sequential record number will be incremented. In short, the file can be   ;
2004: ECAB         ; sequentially read or written once the Read Random has been used to        ;
2005: ECAB         ; position to the required place in the file.                               ;
2006: ECAB         ;                                                                           ;
2007: ECAB         ; To use the Read Random function, you must first open the base extent of   ;
2008: ECAB         ; the file, that is, extent O. Even though there may be no actual data      ;
2009: ECAB         ; records in this extent, opening permits the file to be processed          ;
2010: ECAB         ; correctly.                                                                ;
2011: ECAB         ;  One problem that is not immediately obvious with random files is that    ;
2012: ECAB         ; they can easily be created with gaps in the file. If you were to create   ;
2013: ECAB         ; the file with record number 0 and record number 5000, there would be no   ;
2014: ECAB         ; intervening file extents. Should you attempt to read or copy the file     ;
2015: ECAB         ; sequentially, even using CP/M's file copy utility, only the first extent  ;
2016: ECAB         ; (and in this case, record 0) would get copied. A Read Sequential function ;
2017: ECAB         ; would return an "end of file" error after reading record O. You must      ;
2018: ECAB         ; therefore be conscious of the type of the file that you try and read.     ;
2019: ECAB         ;                                                                           ;
2020: ECAB         ;                                                                           ;
2021: ECAB         ;                                                                           ;
2022: ECAB         ;			Function Code	:   C  = 21H                                    ;
2023: ECAB         ;			Entry Parameters:  DE = Address of File Control Block			;
2024: ECAB         ;			Exit Parameters :	A = 01 (attempt to read unwritten record)   ;
2025: ECAB         ;								A = 03 (CP/M could not close current extent);
2026: ECAB         ;								A = 04 (attempt to read unwritten extent)   ;
2027: ECAB         ;								A = 06 (attempt to read beyond end of disk) ;
2028: ECAB         ;																			;
2029: ECAB         ;------------------------- Read Random - 21 (33) ---------------------------;
2030: ECAB             vReadRandom:
2031: ECAB CD 3D EF               CALL   ReselectDisk         ; Reselect if needed
2032: ECAE
2033: ECAE 0E FF                  LD     C,TRUE               ; Identify as a Read
2034: ECB0 CD 84 F0               CALL   RandomSeek           ; Set up correct Dir entry etc.
2035: ECB3 CC 39 EB               CALL   Z,DiskRead           ; Go Read
2036: ECB6 C9                     RET
2037: ECB7         ;------------------------- Write Random - 22 (34) --------------------------;
2038: ECB7         ; This function writes a specific CP/M record (128 bytes) into a random     ;
2039: ECB7         ; file. It is initiated in much the same way as the companion function,     ;
2040: ECB7         ; Read Random (code 33,21H). It assumes that you have already opened the    ;
2041: ECB7         ; file, set the DMAaddress to the address in memory containing the record to;
2042: ECB7         ; be written to disk, and set the random record number in the FCB to the    ;
2043: ECB7         ; specified record being written. This function also computes the extent in ;
2044: ECB7         ; which the specified record number lies and opens the extent (creating it  ;
2045: ECB7         ; if it does not already exist). The error codes returned in A by this call ;
2046: ECB7         ; are the same as those for Read Random, with the addition of error         ;
2047: ECB7         ; code 05, which indicates a full directory.                                ;
2048: ECB7         ;  Like the Read Random (but unlike the Write Sequential), this function    ;
2049: ECB7         ; does not update the logical extent and sequential (current) record number ;
2050: ECB7         ; in the FCB. Therefore, any subsequent sequential operation will access    ;
2051: ECB7         ; the record just written by the Read Random call, but these functions will ;
2052: ECB7         ; update the sequential record number. The Write Random can therefore be    ;
2053: ECB7         ; used to position to the required place in the file, which can then be     ;
2054: ECB7         ; accessed sequentially.                                                    ;
2055: ECB7         ;                                                                           ;
2056: ECB7         ;  In order to use the Write Random, you must first open the base extent    ;
2057: ECB7         ; (extent 0) of the file. Even though there may be no data records in this  ;
2058: ECB7         ; extent, opening permits the file to be processed correctly.               ;
2059: ECB7         ;  As explained in the notes for the Read Random function, you can easily   ;
2060: ECB7         ; create a random file with gaps in it. If you were to create a file with   ;
2061: ECB7         ; record number 0 and record number 5000, there would be no intervening     ;
2062: ECB7         ; file extents.                                                             ;
2063: ECB7         ;                                                                           ;
2064: ECB7         ;			Function Code	:   C  = 24H                                    ;
2065: ECB7         ;			Entry Parameters:  DE = Address of File Control Block			;
2066: ECB7         ;			Exit Parameters :	A = 01 (attempt to read unwritten record)   ;
2067: ECB7         ;								A = 03 (CP/M could not close current extent);
2068: ECB7         ;								A = 04 (attempt to read unwritten extent)   ;
2069: ECB7         ;								A = 05 (CP/M cannot create new extent)		;
2070: ECB7         ;								A = 06 (attempt to read beyond end of disk) ;
2071: ECB7         ;																			;
2072: ECB7         ;------------------------- Write Random - 22 (34) --------------------------;
2073: ECB7             vWriteRandom:
2074: ECB7 CD 3D EF               CALL   ReselectDisk         ; Reselect if needed
2075: ECBA
